COMPILER BUG: Transitive purity cannot see .handler() calls

Test 1005 identifies that transitive purity analysis cannot see into Zig proc bodies
that use .handler() calls.

Expected:
- compute_with_logging: is_pure=true, is_transitively_pure=FALSE (calls impure log via .handler())

Actual:
- compute_with_logging: is_pure=true, is_transitively_pure=TRUE (WRONG!)

Root cause:
- The purity checker's buildCallGraph() only looks at inline_flows inside procs
- It cannot parse Zig code to find .handler() calls
- When no call graph entry exists, it assumes pure (line 151-155 in purity_checker.zig)

This is different from test 1009, which tests subflows (top-level flows) and WORKS correctly.

Fix needed:
- Option 1: Parse Zig proc bodies to extract .handler() calls (hard)
- Option 2: Default to impure when no call graph exists (safe but conservative)
- Option 3: Require explicit ~[pure] only on procs with no event calls
